Belzberg Is Turning Reins Over to Nephew


By ALISON LEIGH COWAN


Published: March 2, 1991









                    Samuel Belzberg, a 62-year-old financier who rode the takeover wave to become head of one of Canada's foremost dynasties, is surrendering day-to-day control of the centerpiece of his family's empire.        

                    He will hand the reins of the company, the First City Financial Corporation, to his 40-year-old nephew, Brent S. Belzberg.        

                    First City Financial, whose shares are traded on the Toronto Stock Exchange, is the parent company for most of the Belzberg family interests. Though Samuel has run the business as its chief executive for 35 years, he and his older brother, Hyman, and his younger brother, William, each owns 26.7 percent of the company's shares. The public has owned the balance since the mid-1960's.  Two Biggest Holdings        

                    The two biggest holdings of the company are its 89.5 percent stake in First City Trustco Inc., a financial services concern, and a wholly owned real estate development arm, the First City Development Corporation.        

                    The company has had a difficult time in the last year, starting with its disastrous 1989-90 run at Armstrong World Industries, based in Lancaster, Pa. That takeover battle invited a spirited defense from the floor-covering company and the Pennsylvania business establishment. The fight led Pennsylvania to adopt one of the country's toughest anti-takeover laws and ultimately cost the would-be acquirers about $20 million in losses.        

                    The year continued with a second money-losing run at the Asda Group P.L.C., a British retail chain. In addition, the company announced last fall that it was taking huge losses on its securities portfolio and would shut down its trading operations, then run by Marc Belzberg, Samuel's son.        

                    Those setbacks have cost the family dearly. At recent market prices, the three brothers' combined stock holdings in the parent company are worth about $179 million (Canadian), a nice sum but less than a third of what the stakes were worth at the high. And according to one analyst in Vancouver, British Columbia, Tony Yue of Goepel Shields & Partners, the parent company has essentially given back in the last 14 months the money it made speculating in takeover stocks in the 1980's.        

                    The company acknowledged yesterday that the last year had been trying. "First City Financial has experienced a significant erosion in shareholder value over the last year, and faces a very difficult year of asset restructuring and debt refinancing," Brent Belzberg said in the statement.        

                    The transition, which calls for Brent to assume the title of chief executive from his uncle, was decided at a First City board meeting on Thursday in Toronto and is effective immediately. Brent will also pick up the chief executive title at First City Trustco and keep his titles as chief executive of First City Trust, the operating unit of Trustco, and of First City Development. Samuel will remain chairman of the parent company.        

                    The moves, following the company's decision last fall to close the New York trading operation, an office that speculated on takeover stocks, signal a further retreat for the Belzberg family from the takeover business that has shaped much of its dealings over the last decade and an effort to refocus on its two core operating companies.        

                    "It reflects the strategic changes that are going on and just confirms that the company is not going to be involved in takeovers and securities transactions in the future," said Eric W. Evans, First City spokesman. "The intention is to be strictly a holding company for those two businesses."        

                    Brent alone of the family's second generation has held significant management positions at both operating companies, which may have favored him over other contenders, analysts and others close to the family said yesterday. A lawyer who graduated from the University of Toronto, he spent a few years practicing securities law at Tory, Tory, DesLauriers & Bennington, a Canadian law firm, before joining the family business, Mr. Evans said.        

                    "Sam made a decision that was best for the company and for the shareholders," said Byron Menides, a Worcester, Mass., executive who has served on the board of a Belzberg-controlled company. "Marc is very good at what he does, but for all the time I've known him he's not been used as a manager. So Brent is the logical successor."        

                    While Brent's younger brother, Murray, is expected to continue as an executive in the First City Trust, Marc's future with the company is less clear once he finishes shutting down the New York trading office. "He won't actively be involved in the business because there really isn't a role, given the change in direction of the company," Mr. Evans said.        

                    First City Financial's stock closed yesterday at $4, up 25 cents.        

                    Photos: Brent S. Belzberg, left, to whom Samuel Belzberg is surrendering day-to-day control of the First City Financial Corporation, talked with his father, Hyman Belzberg, at the 1989 annual meeting of First City Trustco, in which First City Financial owns an 89 percent stake (Canadian Press) (pg. 31); Samuel Belzberg has run First City Financial Corporation for the past 35 years as its chief executive. (The New York Times) (pg. 33)        








 














 
























 








 

